Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Coronavirus (COVID-19) cases have been confirmed in Trinidad and Tobago. The Trinbagonian authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
Local measures
A “stay at home” order, for the non-essential labour force, is in place until at least 15 May, and, following further testing, the Government will review changes to these measures on 10 May. It is also now mandatory to wear masks, to cover noses and mouths, in public spaces. You should adhere to all precautionary measures put in place by the local authorities.
Schools and universities are also closed.
The Trinidad and Tobago government has set up a COVID-19 hotline staffed by doctors. If you suspect you have any symptoms please contact the hotline on +1 868 877-WELL (9355) from Trinidad or +1 868 800-HEAL (4325) toll-free from Tobago. You should not report to any healthcare facility but instead self-quarantine and follow instructions provided by the authorities.
Travel restrictions
The Trinidad and Tobago government indefinitely closed its borders to all international flights from midnight 22 March. Sea borders are also closed indefinitely to all vessels including yachts.
The Trinidad and Tobago authorities previously introduced a ban on the entry of non-nationals after midnight on Tuesday 17 March.
For information on how to return to the UK from Trinidad and Tobago, see Return to the UK.
All international arrivals into Trinidad and Tobago are required to self-isolate for a period of 14 days. Further information and guidance is available at www.health.gov.tt.
The Trinidad and Tobago authorities have announced a ban on cruise ships entering until the end of the current cruise season.
Local measures
Schools and universities are closed.
The Trinidad and Tobago authorities have set up a hotline if you have coronavirus symptoms or concerns about your risk of exposure to coronavirus. The number to call from Trinidad is +1 868 877-WELL (9355) and from Tobago +1 868 800-HEAL (4325) toll-free.
